10:31.364 --> 10:34.534 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Another thing that
Mr. Trump spoke
a lot about on the campaign
trail was Common

10:34.567 --> 10:35.902 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Core.

10:35.935 --> 10:36.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He is against it.

10:36.936 --> 10:38.171 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He doesn't like it.

10:38.204 --> 10:41.407 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What do we know about Betsy
DeVos' position
on Common Core?

10:41.441 --> 10:45.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Well, she's
clarified her position
on Common Core today, saying
that she thinks

10:45.211 --> 10:47.380 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it's a federal boondoggle.

10:47.413 --> 10:52.185 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's also said that she's in
favor of accountability
and local control.

10:52.218 --> 10:56.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some school choice advocates had
actually
been worried that DeVos was a
Common Core

10:56.222 --> 11:02.428 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
supporter because she's on the
board of Governor
Jeb Bush's organization, and
obviously Governor

11:02.462 --> 11:04.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bush is quite a supporter of
Common Core.

11:04.197 --> 11:08.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But she made it clear today that
she stands
with Mr. Trump in opposing the
standards.

11:08.301 --> 11:11.170 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: How does she compare,
her background
compare?

11:11.204 --> 11:12.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She was a philanthropist.

11:12.939 --> 11:16.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She was a chairman of the
Michigan Republican
Party.

11:16.042 --> 11:20.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How does her background and her
experience
compare with previous education
secretaries?

11:20.747 --> 11:22.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: It's unusual
background.

11:22.582 --> 11:26.653 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have never that I can think
of really had
an advocate at the helm of the
department.

11:26.686 --> 11:32.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Our last couple education
secretaries, Secretary
John King, who is in the post
now, Arne Duncan,

11:32.825 --> 11:38.264 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Obama's first education
secretary, had both
worked in school districts, had
been -- John

11:38.298 --> 11:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
King was the state chief in New
York.

11:40.466 --> 11:43.937 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Arne Duncan was a school
superintendent in
Chicago.

11:43.970 --> 11:47.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Other education secretaries,
like Lamar Alexander,
actually, have been governors.

11:47.707 --> 11:51.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So it's unusual to have somebody
who has primarily
been an advocate.

11:51.344 --> 11:53.913 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: She's never worked in
public education.

11:53.947 --> 11:57.216 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
She's never run a big
bureaucracy or a big
organization.

11:57.250 --> 11:58.217 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is that what you're saying?

11:58.251 --> 11:59.686 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Yes, that's
correct.

11:59.719 --> 12:02.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: What's been the
reaction to her
being named as his nominee?

12:03.022 --> 12:05.124 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Depends on who you
ask.

12:05.158 --> 12:09.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
School choice advocates are
really excited
to have one of their own, one of
their champions

12:09.195 --> 12:11.464 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
headed to the Department of
Education.

12:11.497 --> 12:14.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Teachers unions are really
unhappy with the
pick.

12:14.867 --> 12:18.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They picked up on what you
picked up on, that
she doesn't have a background in
a school

12:18.137 --> 12:19.839 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
district.

12:19.872 --> 12:22.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they are also opposed to
this idea of
vouchers, which they say siphon
off money

12:22.408 --> 12:23.943 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for public schools.

12:23.977 --> 12:27.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And that's been an
issue for some
time now in public education.

12:27.513 --> 12:29.315 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Yes, absolutely.

12:29.349 --> 12:33.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The idea of creating a federal
school choice
program has been something that
Republicans

12:33.453 --> 12:35.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have wanted to do for a really
long time.

12:35.688 --> 12:39.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The closest they have come is a
voucher program
for the District of Columbia.

12:39.158 --> 12:43.329 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But with DeVos in the Education
Department,
they may really be able to that
vision further.

12:43.363 --> 12:46.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Any sense will she
have any trouble
getting confirmed, do you think?

12:46.132 --> 12:47.767 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: I would expect
not.

12:47.800 --> 12:51.804 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Senator Alexander put out a very
supportive
statement on her confirmation
today.

12:51.838 --> 12:55.775 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
She's certainly donated to a lot
of Republicans.

12:55.808 --> 12:58.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so they may really look upon
her appointment
favorably.

12:58.811 --> 13:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Alyson Klein helping
us understand
who Betsy DeVos is, thanks so
much for coming

13:03.282 --> 13:04.250 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in.

13:04.283 --> 13:12.458 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ALYSON KLEIN: Thanks for having
me.

13:12.492 --> 13:20.199 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One area of
uncharted territory
under a Trump presidency centers
on potential

13:20.233 --> 13:22.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
conflicts of interests with his
businesses.

13:22.669 --> 13:28.474 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Yesterday, the president-elect
told The New
York Times, "The law is totally
on my side."

13:28.508 --> 13:33.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But recent meetings with some
current and
potential foreign investors have
raised new

13:33.746 --> 13:34.714 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
questions.

13:34.747 --> 13:36.683 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We explore those now with
Richard Painter.

13:36.716 --> 13:42.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's a University of Minnesota
law professor
who was President George W.
Bush's top ethics

13:42.121 --> 13:44.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
attorney in the White House.

13:44.090 --> 13:49.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Kenneth Gross, he's an
ethics law expert
who advised New York Mayor
Michael Bloomberg

13:49.562 --> 13:53.032 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
when he went from businessman to
public official.

13:53.066 --> 13:55.068 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we welcome both of you to
the "NewsHour."

13:55.101 --> 13:56.869 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm going to start with you,
Richard Painter.

13:56.903 --> 14:03.676 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When Donald Trump says the
president can't
have a conflict of interest, is
he right about

14:03.710 --> 14:04.844 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
that?

14:04.877 --> 14:06.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD PAINTER, University of
Minnesota:
Well, no.

14:06.446 --> 14:09.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course the president can have
a conflict
of interest.

14:09.649 --> 14:14.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, think about where we
would be today
if President Roosevelt had owned
the buildings

14:14.921 --> 14:20.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Germany during the war or the
years leading
up to the war and large loans
from Deutsche

14:20.660 --> 14:22.361 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Bank.

14:22.395 --> 14:28.468 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can have conflicts of
interest that are
very detrimental to the American
people.

14:28.501 --> 14:32.305 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You need a president who is
going to stand
up to foreign dictators, who is
going to focus

14:32.338 --> 14:38.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the needs of the United
States, and the
need for peace in the world and
also strength.

14:38.311 --> 14:41.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And these conflicts of interest
are real.

14:41.380 --> 14:46.619 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether or not a specific
federal criminal
statute applies to the
president, which it

14:46.652 --> 14:51.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
doesn't, even though it applies
to every other
executive branch employee, but
there are other

14:51.624 --> 14:56.195 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
rules that do apply to the
president, including
the Emoluments Clause of the
Constitution,

14:56.229 --> 15:01.367 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which says the president cannot
receive payments
from foreign governments.

15:01.400 --> 15:05.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's something the Trump
Organization
needs to deal with, because they
have outstanding

15:05.805 --> 15:09.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
loans from the Bank of China,
which is controlled
by the government of China.

15:09.742 --> 15:15.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they have foreign diplomats
checking into
their hotels and renting the
expensive suites.

15:15.214 --> 15:16.883 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that needs to be dealt with.

15:16.916 --> 15:21.020 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the law does apply to the
president and
he can have conflicts of
interest, and he

15:21.053 --> 15:22.188 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
needs to get rid of them.

15:22.221 --> 15:23.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Kenneth Gross,
how do you see
that?

15:23.890 --> 15:27.393 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How clear are the rules, the
laws that apply
to the president?

15:27.426 --> 15:32.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KENNETH GROSS, Ethics Law
Expert: Well, what's
clear is that the domestic
conflict of interest

15:32.298 --> 15:34.634 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
law doesn't apply to the
president.

15:34.667 --> 15:37.336 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the letter of the law.

15:37.370 --> 15:44.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What the ethics surrounding a
president and
what the conventions say he
should be doing

15:44.510 --> 15:46.445 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is a very different thing.

15:46.479 --> 15:51.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Emoluments Clause, as
Richard has mentioned,
which is this gift provision
from the original

15:51.551 --> 15:56.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Constitution, but is alive and
well today,
does apply, but the application
of that is

15:56.923 --> 15:58.291 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not so clear.

15:58.324 --> 16:01.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, what sort of foreign
corporations
would come into play?

16:01.327 --> 16:06.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are they really owned by a
foreign government
and exactly is what an
emolument?

16:06.432 --> 16:10.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is it just a payment or does it
actually have
to be a benefit...

16:10.136 --> 16:11.204 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A kind of
benefit.

16:11.237 --> 16:12.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KENNETH GROSS: ... if it's a
commercial transaction?

16:12.371 --> 16:15.474 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, yes, there are issues of
interpretation
as well.

16:15.508 --> 16:21.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Richard Painter,
what do you
say Donald Trump needing to do
in order to

16:21.414 --> 16:27.186 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
remove any question of a
conflict of interest,
given his significant and
widespread holdings?

16:27.220 --> 16:32.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD PAINTER: Well, I think
the first step
is to make sure that he complies
with the

16:32.792 --> 16:38.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Constitution, and he does need
to address
the emoluments issue.

16:38.064 --> 16:44.203 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I have suggested to his
transition team
that they ought to have an
assignment over

16:44.237 --> 16:50.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to the United States government,
an assignment
of any and all payments from
foreign governments

16:50.343 --> 16:53.546 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that are covered by the
Emoluments Clause.

16:53.579 --> 16:56.415 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is an answer to the problem
of a gift
from a foreign government.

16:56.449 --> 16:58.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You can give it to the United
States government.

16:58.751 --> 17:04.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He could do that today with a
simple assignment
of those payments, plus an audit
that would

17:04.957 --> 17:07.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take place every year to make
sure we swept
them all out.

17:07.994 --> 17:09.729 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's the bare minimum.

17:09.762 --> 17:12.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the Electoral
College ought to
insist on that before voting,
just as they

17:12.965 --> 17:17.570 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would want to see a birth
certificate if that
were at issue or anything else.

17:17.603 --> 17:18.571 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
That's important
constitutionally.

17:18.604 --> 17:20.373 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

17:20.406 --> 17:23.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Richard Painter,
let me just
stop you right there, because I
want to make

17:23.175 --> 17:26.445 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sure what everybody understands
what this
emoluments business is.

17:26.479 --> 17:32.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what we're talking about is
anything that
would benefit Donald Trump's
businesses, being

17:32.618 --> 17:37.189 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sure that doesn't benefit --
doesn't interfere
in any way with the U.S.
government.

17:37.223 --> 17:38.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KENNETH GROSS: Yes.

17:38.224 --> 17:39.592 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
As well as I can define this...

17:39.625 --> 17:40.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICHARD PAINTER: Well, no,
that's too broad.

17:40.626 --> 17:41.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's too broad.

17:41.627 --> 17:42.595 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: OK.

17:42.628 --> 17:43.596 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
KENNETH GROSS: OK.

17:43.629 --> 17:45.331 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

17:45.364 --> 17:48.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what we have here is a
provision in the
Constitution that says you
cannot receive

17:48.634 --> 17:51.103 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a present, meaning a gift.

17:51.137 --> 17:53.806 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then there is this question of
emolument.

17:53.839 --> 17:58.444 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It clearly applies to someone
who works in
the National Institute of Health
that wants

17:58.477 --> 18:01.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
to work for a foreign
government, because
he's providing a service.

18:01.814 --> 18:07.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if he gets a payment for
that, that raises
questions under emoluments and
has to be dealt

18:07.386 --> 18:09.522 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with by the Department of
Justice.

18:09.555 --> 18:16.529 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If there's a commercial
transaction, a foreign
government is paying rent into a
place that

18:16.562 --> 18:21.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're renting that is owned by
Mr. Trump,
the president of the United
States, that -- I

18:21.300 --> 18:25.304 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have not seen the emolument
provision applied
in quite that situation.

18:25.338 --> 18:26.439 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not a service.

18:26.472 --> 18:28.207 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a commercial transaction.

18:28.240 --> 18:30.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, without
getting too much
in the weeds here in the few
minutes that

18:30.309 --> 18:36.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we have, Richard Painter, how do
you see -- again,
what are you saying that Mr.
Trump needs to

18:36.682 --> 18:38.517 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
do?

18:38.551 --> 18:42.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD PAINTER: Well, if those
are above-market
rents or they're below-market
interest rate

18:42.455 --> 18:48.728 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
loans from the Bank of China, I
think those
are presents, just like any
other present.

18:48.761 --> 18:53.132 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the point is that he could
right now assign
over to the United States
government anything

18:53.165 --> 18:57.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
covered under the Emoluments
Clause of the
Constitution, and we can sort
out later what

18:57.870 --> 18:59.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
it is, pursuant under audit.

18:59.839 --> 19:02.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that needs to be done before
the Electoral
College vote.

19:02.508 --> 19:08.014 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The broad issue can be addressed
by divesting
himself of all of his assets
through an initial

19:08.047 --> 19:12.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
public offering or some other
way to convert
the assets to cash.

19:12.651 --> 19:16.756 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many American families do that
when they want
to move on from their business.

19:16.789 --> 19:19.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, here, there's a very good
reason to move
on.

19:19.225 --> 19:21.260 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He's going to become the
president of the
United States.

19:21.293 --> 19:25.331 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But, Ken Gross,
he has talked
about putting his assets in what
is called

19:25.364 --> 19:28.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a blind trust that his children
would run.

19:28.134 --> 19:30.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Would that take care of what
we're talking
about?

19:30.102 --> 19:32.705 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
KENNETH GROSS: It really
doesn't.

19:32.738 --> 19:34.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not a blind trust, first of
all.

19:34.407 --> 19:36.175 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He knows what he put in it.

19:36.208 --> 19:40.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In order for it to be a true
blind trust,
he would have to liquidate his
assets first.

19:40.780 --> 19:43.616 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is not realistic in any
kind of short
period of time.

19:43.649 --> 19:45.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I don't know about going public
with everything.

19:45.918 --> 19:47.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's not so easy either.

19:47.686 --> 19:53.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I understand that most his
assets are
illiquid, and they don't all
create conflicts

19:53.959 --> 19:55.227 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of interests.

19:55.261 --> 19:57.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think -- I agree that you need
to look internationally
first.

19:57.630 --> 20:03.269 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But having a trust with your
children in charge
doesn't meet the requirements of
blind trust,

20:03.302 --> 20:06.105 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
if he were required to meet
those requirements,
which he's not.

20:06.138 --> 20:09.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Richard Painter,
just quickly,
how much of this is complicated
by the fact

20:09.809 --> 20:14.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we don't know publicly what
Donald Trump's
business interests are?

20:14.914 --> 20:17.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He has not released his tax
returns.

20:17.550 --> 20:22.755 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He has made a financial
statement, but a lot
of this is not public
information, is it?

20:22.788 --> 20:24.557 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD PAINTER: No, it's not.

20:24.590 --> 20:28.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I urged him to release the
tax returns
during the campaign, but he
decided not to

20:28.360 --> 20:31.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
do that, even though every other
candidate
has and every president.

20:31.497 --> 20:37.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, going forward, I think the
answer here
is for him to sell these
business interests,

20:37.136 --> 20:40.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
take the company public or come
up with some
other answer.

20:40.306 --> 20:44.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It will leave him with a few
billion dollars
to give some to his kids, and
put the rest

20:44.276 --> 20:46.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in a blind trust, and be a good
president.

20:46.846 --> 20:52.351 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And he made this decision that
he wants to
be a president, rather than a
businessman.

20:52.384 --> 20:55.154 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now that he's made that
decision and he
won, it's time to do it.

20:55.187 --> 20:59.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, Ken Gross,
just quickly,
is that what he has to do, sell
it all off

20:59.959 --> 21:01.360 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
and...

21:01.393 --> 21:03.696 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KENNETH GROSS: I'm not going
that far, because
it's not realistic.

21:03.729 --> 21:07.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think, internationally,
though, that's where
the primary focus should be.

21:07.333 --> 21:11.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Kenneth Gross,
Richard Painter,
we thank you both.

21:11.904 --> 21:18.677 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
RICHARD PAINTER: Thanks.

21:18.711 --> 21:27.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: During his run
for the White
House, president-elect Donald
Trump made Mexico,

21:27.186 --> 21:31.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
perhaps more than any other
individual country,
a campaign issue.

21:31.290 --> 21:36.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, with the help of the
Pulitzer Center
on Crisis Reporting, we begin a
special two-part

21:36.562 --> 21:42.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
series from Mexico, and a look
at Trump's
promises to deport millions of
undocumented

21:42.601 --> 21:47.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
immigrants and to build a wall
along the U.S.
Southern border.

21:47.206 --> 21:52.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Nick
Schifrin and producer
Zach Fannin begin their report
tonight from

21:52.111 --> 21:56.248 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the outskirts of the Mexican
border city of
Ciudad Juarez.

21:56.282 --> 22:02.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: In the dry
riverbed that separates
Mexico from the U.S., the
promise of a better

22:02.087 --> 22:05.090 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
life is only a few hundred feet
away.

22:05.124 --> 22:10.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The woman is a 23-year-old
Mexican from Juarez
who asked to remain anonymous.

22:10.362 --> 22:14.133 align:left position:25%,start line:80% size:75%
Leading her is a
half-guide/half-smuggler
known as a coyote.

22:14.166 --> 22:16.602 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Everything beyond the fence is
El Paso, Texas.

22:16.635 --> 22:18.170 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
She's trying to cross illegally.

22:18.204 --> 22:22.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
There's work here,
but the wages are very low.

22:22.875 --> 22:24.710 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can barely survive here.

22:24.743 --> 22:26.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Life there is better than here.

22:26.345 --> 22:29.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: The coyote's been
doing this
for 10 years.

22:29.348 --> 22:32.551 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Compared to when he started,
today's border
is much more secure.

22:32.585 --> 22:35.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): It's
more difficult
now.

22:35.988 --> 22:38.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Before, they used to cross just
to have fun.

22:38.457 --> 22:42.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now they cross because they want
to be there,
like her, and live there.

22:42.761 --> 22:45.698 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: She's part of a
recent spike.

22:45.731 --> 22:49.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
From August to October, the
number of people
apprehended on the Southern
border rose by

22:49.301 --> 22:50.903 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
nearly 20 percent.

22:50.936 --> 22:53.639 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
She's trying to get in before
Donald Trump
is inaugurated.

22:53.672 --> 22:58.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): They
say it will
get more difficult, so I have to
do it now.

22:58.777 --> 23:03.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: What would happen
if President
Trump built a wall right here?

23:03.249 --> 23:05.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN (through translator): We
would cross anyway.

23:05.918 --> 23:07.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're never going to stop
crossing.

23:07.620 --> 23:10.723 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: How would you
cross if there
were a wall there?

23:10.756 --> 23:13.826 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): That's
what we wondered
when the fence went up.

23:13.859 --> 23:15.027 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we found a way.

23:15.060 --> 23:16.061 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Here we are.

23:16.095 --> 23:17.563 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's always a way.

23:17.596 --> 23:19.064 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: It's not easy.

23:19.098 --> 23:21.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Tonight, a border guard scared
them away.

23:21.133 --> 23:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They will try again tomorrow.

23:23.202 --> 23:26.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Stopping this kind of illegal
immigration
was a central Trump campaign
theme.

23:26.538 --> 23:30.542 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DONALD TRUMP (R),
President-Elect: When Mexico
sends its people, they're not
sending their

23:30.576 --> 23:31.543 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
best.

23:31.577 --> 23:33.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're bringing drugs.

23:33.212 --> 23:34.179 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They're bringing crime.

23:34.213 --> 23:35.180 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They're rapists.

23:35.214 --> 23:38.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And some, I assume, are good
people.

23:38.817 --> 23:48.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On day one, we will begin
working on an impenetrable,
physical, tall, powerful,
beautiful Southern

23:48.661 --> 23:50.329 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
border wall.

23:50.362 --> 23:52.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
(CHEERING AND APPLAUSE)

23:52.898 --> 23:58.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: The Mexico-U.S.
border is nearly
2,000 miles' long.

23:58.470 --> 24:03.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, walls or fences, like
this one
west of El Paso, Texas, cover
about 700 miles.

24:03.542 --> 24:04.977 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
The terrain can be rough.

24:05.010 --> 24:08.881 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the distances between
American and Mexican
cities are often small.

24:08.914 --> 24:13.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In some places, sturdy iron
gives way to standard-issue
chain-link fence, which is
scheduled to be

24:13.819 --> 24:14.787 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
replaced.

24:14.820 --> 24:20.292 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This fence couldn't keep this
young man out.

24:20.326 --> 24:27.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. border agents arrest a
17-year-old Mexican
who crossed illegally.

24:27.499 --> 24:31.904 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's been arrested before trying
to lead undocumented
immigrants into the U.S.

24:31.937 --> 24:36.375 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This time, he was spotted by a
highly sensitive
camera manned by an agent more
than a mile

24:36.408 --> 24:38.277 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
away.

24:38.310 --> 24:39.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOE ROMERO, Border Patrol: They
have got nighttime
equipment, cameras they can use
to look down

24:39.912 --> 24:43.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and really cover a vast area
with the technology
they have available to them.

24:43.349 --> 24:46.785 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Joe Romero is a
supervisory
Border Patrol agent.

24:46.819 --> 24:50.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says there is no quick and
easy solution
to securing the border.

24:50.222 --> 24:53.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOE ROMERO: Here, we have got an
18-foot fence.

24:53.092 --> 24:56.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a guy in Mexico, I'm
sure, making
a killing off of 20-foot
ladders.

24:57.029 --> 25:00.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At the end of the day, people
find a way to
get through.

25:00.866 --> 25:04.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Every day, they
patrol for
eight hours.

25:04.737 --> 25:11.944 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The vehicles and fences are
meant to deter
and stop would-be crossers.

25:11.977 --> 25:17.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This increased presence, along
with more aggressive
prosecution, began a decade ago.

25:17.182 --> 25:18.717 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It worked.

25:18.751 --> 25:25.357 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Illegal crossings are down 84
percent since
2006, despite the recent spike.

25:25.391 --> 25:28.060 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is the goal to bring illegal
crossings to
zero?

25:28.093 --> 25:30.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOE ROMERO: I can't say that you
will ever
be able to stop crossings 100
percent.

25:30.929 --> 25:31.897 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I just don't see that.

25:31.930 --> 25:33.165 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, really, that's not the
goal.

25:33.198 --> 25:35.701 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The goal is to mitigate the
threats coming
to our borders.

25:35.734 --> 25:40.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Truly separating
these countries
is nearly impossible, given
their deep connections,

25:40.672 --> 25:44.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not only geographic -- I'm
standing in the
U.S., and everything beyond the
water is Mexico

25:44.943 --> 25:48.947 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
-- but also intertwined
economies and families
who straddle the border.

25:48.981 --> 25:55.421 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Every day, more than a million
people cross
legally.

25:55.454 --> 26:00.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Olivares Castro family's
commute starts
every day at 4:00 a.m.

26:00.692 --> 26:04.897 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Mother Reina, behind the wheel,
is a Mexican
from Juarez; 12-year-old Anna
wants to be

26:04.930 --> 26:06.465 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a doctor when she grows up.

26:06.498 --> 26:10.402 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To cross the border, she needs a
binder full
of papers and a student visa.

26:10.436 --> 26:14.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
About 370,000 vehicles cross the
Southern
border every day.

26:14.506 --> 26:19.144 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The wait can be more than an
hour, all of
this, so Anna can go to an
American school

26:19.178 --> 26:20.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that's better than any school in
Juarez.

26:20.979 --> 26:22.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNA OLIVARES CASTRO, Student:
They teach
you more things.

26:22.314 --> 26:25.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They get more deep into the
subjects they
teach you.

26:25.217 --> 26:27.085 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I have more job opportunities.

26:27.119 --> 26:28.654 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They recognize your talent.

26:28.687 --> 26:32.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: She says this
private school
treats her with respect.

26:32.057 --> 26:36.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This family and many Mexicans
believe that
president-elect Trump
disrespects a country

26:36.895 --> 26:38.397 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of 120 million.

26:38.430 --> 26:41.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REINA OLIVARES CASTRO, Mother
(translated):
Not everyone is a criminal.

26:42.000 --> 26:45.604 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They need us Mexicans, they need
us Latinos,
and we need them.

26:45.637 --> 26:47.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANNA OLIVARES CASTRO: He's
telling lies.

26:47.306 --> 26:51.043 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And all those people think that
we're what
Donald Trump says.

26:51.076 --> 26:53.078 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But we're not like that.

26:53.111 --> 26:54.913 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We're good people.

26:54.947 --> 26:58.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Two thousand
three hundreds
miles north, the Latino
community in Columbus,

26:58.884 --> 27:01.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ohio, feels the same frustration
and fear.

27:01.420 --> 27:10.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN RAMOS, LULAC: Here in the
Midwest, in
Ohio, now all Latinos seems to
fit a profile.

27:11.029 --> 27:15.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: John Ramos heads
the local
office of the pro-Latino rights
organization

27:15.234 --> 27:16.869 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
LULAC.

27:16.902 --> 27:19.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He is most concerned by Trump's
promise to
deport millions of undocumented
workers.

27:19.538 --> 27:27.513 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DONALD TRUMP: I am going to
create a new special
deportation task force focused
on identifying

27:27.546 --> 27:34.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and quickly removing the most
dangerous criminal
illegal immigrants in America
who have evaded

27:34.887 --> 27:36.755 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
justice.

27:36.788 --> 27:41.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: That promise
seems to have
awakened previously hidden
racism and nationalism.

27:41.660 --> 27:45.898 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This undocumented Mexican
immigrant, who was
too scared to show her face,
gave birth nine

27:45.931 --> 27:47.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
months ago in Ohio.

27:47.699 --> 27:51.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That means the daughter's a U.S.
citizen,
and the U.S. is obligated to
provide her Social

27:51.436 --> 27:53.138 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Security.

27:53.171 --> 27:56.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when the mother tried to get
her baby
a Social Security card, a local
official threw

27:56.575 --> 27:57.809 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
her out of the office.

27:57.843 --> 28:01.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator): He
told me: "I
can't help you.

28:01.513 --> 28:02.548 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Get out of here."

28:02.581 --> 28:03.715 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And his voice was upset.

28:03.749 --> 28:06.418 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I told him: "It's not Social
Security for
me.

28:06.451 --> 28:07.519 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It's for her."

28:07.553 --> 28:09.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he told me: "You don't have
documents.

28:09.354 --> 28:10.622 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How dare you come here?"

28:10.656 --> 28:14.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: Is that a federal
official
effectively going rogue?

28:14.092 --> 28:16.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN RAMOS: I would say so.

28:16.295 --> 28:25.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not in his position as a
Social Security
employee, federal employee, to
request a person

28:25.704 --> 28:27.472 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to show proof of their
citizenship.

28:27.506 --> 28:30.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: The mother
returned with a
lawyer, and the government
official gave the

28:30.609 --> 28:32.544 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
baby the Social Security card.

28:32.578 --> 28:35.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he improperly forced the
mother to provide
her address.

28:35.514 --> 28:37.416 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ramos says that's never happened
before.

28:37.449 --> 28:43.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN RAMOS: If you have to
provide right now
your residence, your point of
contact, your

28:43.755 --> 28:50.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
phone number, you're providing a
track, a
documentation to follow up on
you.

28:50.696 --> 28:54.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NICK SCHIFRIN: And that has sent
a chill into
Columbus' Latino community.

28:54.933 --> 28:57.903 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN RAMOS: It's all the hate.

28:57.936 --> 29:06.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's all these comments that he
would say
about, like, "Oh, I would just
punch him in

29:06.044 --> 29:07.279 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
