31:41.333 --> 31:47.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Now: trying to reverse
radicalization and
terrorism in the U.S.

31:47.139 --> 31:51.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien looks at how
experts in the
field of clinical psychology are
tackling

31:51.910 --> 31:55.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this, as part of our weekly
story on the Leading
Edge of science.

31:55.514 --> 32:01.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: In a federal
courtroom in Minneapolis,
they are facing the threat of
homegrown terrorism

32:01.386 --> 32:05.590 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in a manner that has never been
tried before
in this country.

32:05.624 --> 32:09.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It is a bold experiment in
criminal justice
and clinical psychology.

32:09.728 --> 32:11.696 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
The question?

32:11.730 --> 32:16.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Can aggressive counseling bring
someone back
from the brink of
radicalization?

32:16.234 --> 32:18.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MANNY ATWAL, Federal Public
Defender: What
we have started here is
revolutionary.

32:18.470 --> 32:20.305 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I think it's great.

32:20.338 --> 32:25.110 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Manny Atwal is a
federal public
defender representing
20-year-old Abdullahi

32:25.143 --> 32:26.845 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yusuf.

32:26.878 --> 32:32.484 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He is one of eight
first-generation Somali
Americans, all in their teens or
early 20s,

32:32.517 --> 32:36.788 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
convicted in May of plotting to
go to Syria
and fight for the Islamic State.

32:36.822 --> 32:39.024 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MANNY ATWAL: I know we punish
juveniles.

32:39.057 --> 32:41.493 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I get that, and I understand
that.

32:41.526 --> 32:44.229 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I know we punish young
adults, and I get
that and understand that.

32:44.262 --> 32:48.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, at the same time, to say
let's just lock
them up for a lifetime is not
the right solution.

32:48.633 --> 32:53.905 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: While he was in
jail awaiting
sentencing, Abdullahi Yusuf
became the nation's

32:53.939 --> 32:58.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first convicted terrorist to
undergo terrorism
rehabilitation.

32:58.710 --> 33:03.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He has two mentors who counsel
him regularly
and a wide-ranging reading list.

33:03.648 --> 33:07.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MANNY ATWAL: He will have like a
week to read
this, write up a book report and
then discuss

33:07.719 --> 33:08.787 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it with us.

33:08.820 --> 33:09.955 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: So, it's a real
assignment
for him?

33:09.988 --> 33:11.423 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MANNY ATWAL: Yes.

33:11.456 --> 33:13.225 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Yes.

33:13.258 --> 33:16.194 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Learning American civics,
learning about American
culture, learning about the East
and West

33:16.228 --> 33:18.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just -- it just opened up his
eyes.

33:18.563 --> 33:23.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that, I think, is the
disengagement that
I speak of, to try and get these
kids to disengage

33:23.702 --> 33:28.907 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from some of their thinking
that's been put
in their heads, and to get them
back to be

33:28.940 --> 33:31.443 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
good citizens that they were
before this all
happened.

33:31.476 --> 33:35.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: It appears the
effort might
have held sway with the judge.

33:35.647 --> 33:40.886 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yusuf, who also testified
against his friends,
was sentenced to time served.

33:40.919 --> 33:43.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Most of the others received long
prison terms.

33:43.755 --> 33:47.559 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The case of these men is one
chapter in a
long, sad story.

33:47.592 --> 33:51.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JOHN TUNHEIM, Chief U.S.
District Judge, District
of Minnesota: Minnesota has the
greatest number

33:51.763 --> 33:56.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of terrorism prosecutions of any
of the federal
districts in the United States.

33:56.568 --> 34:02.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: John Tunheim is
the chief federal
judge for the District of
Minnesota, home

34:02.207 --> 34:06.211 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the largest Somali American
community in
the U.S.

34:06.244 --> 34:14.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He watched from the bench as a
tragic exodus
began in 2007; 23 young Somali
Americans from

34:14.085 --> 34:20.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Minnesota joined the ranks of
the al-Qaida-linked
Al-Shabaab terror group as it
tried to topple

34:20.358 --> 34:25.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the government of Somalia.

34:25.330 --> 34:29.434 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
More recently, the call to arms
has come from
the Islamic State.

34:29.467 --> 34:34.673 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For judges trying to mete out
fair sentences,
it is uncharted territory.

34:34.706 --> 34:36.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There are no guidelines.

34:36.374 --> 34:41.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TUNHEIM: They're different
from a bank
robber or someone who sells
drugs.

34:41.713 --> 34:43.181 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, we understand those
cases.

34:43.214 --> 34:45.884 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have had many of those cases
in our courts.

34:45.917 --> 34:48.019 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We haven't had many terrorism
cases.

34:48.053 --> 34:49.821 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We need to understand them.

34:49.854 --> 34:55.193 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We need to make sure that we can
keep them,
to the best effort that we
possibly can, from

34:55.226 --> 34:56.895 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
becoming terrorists again.

34:56.928 --> 35:00.532 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: For some expert
advice, they
turned to this man in Stuttgart,
Germany.

35:00.565 --> 35:04.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL KOEHLER, German Institute
on Radicalization
and De-radicalization: The
Minneapolis group

35:04.736 --> 35:07.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was a by-the-book radicalization
process.

35:07.706 --> 35:13.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What they did was, they actually
followed
ISIL's own recruitment handbook
step-by-step.

35:13.078 --> 35:18.249 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Daniel Koehler is
one of a
small cohort of experts in the
world in the

35:18.283 --> 35:21.786 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
emerging field of
de-radicalization.

35:21.820 --> 35:27.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The judge hearing the cases in
Minnesota is
factoring Koehler's guidance
into sentencing.

35:27.325 --> 35:32.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DANIEL KOEHLER: When you start
working with
a person, the first question is,
is that person

35:32.664 --> 35:34.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
willing to change?

35:34.232 --> 35:38.470 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is he or she actually asking for
help to leave
the movement?

35:38.503 --> 35:40.105 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is there any cognitive opening?

35:40.138 --> 35:41.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's like peeling an onion.

35:41.940 --> 35:46.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Layer by layer, you try to work
yourself to
the core and offer something
that gets more

35:46.244 --> 35:51.883 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and more attractive to that
person, to compete
with a narrative of groups like
ISIL or al-Qaida.

35:51.916 --> 35:57.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Koehler has
de-radicalized
neo-Nazis for years, and he says
the approach

35:57.222 --> 36:03.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is much the same, but the
enticement to religious
extremism is even more
compelling.

36:03.361 --> 36:06.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARIE KRUGLANSKI, Psychologist,
University
of Maryland: It's the
opportunity to become

36:06.131 --> 36:10.368 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a hero, to become a martyr, to
serve a cause
greater than your own.

36:10.402 --> 36:16.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Psychologist Arie
Kruglanski
says terrorists are seeking that
and certainty,

36:16.608 --> 36:19.544 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
clear-cut answers in a chaotic
world.

36:19.577 --> 36:22.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The psychological term is
cognitive closure.

36:22.313 --> 36:26.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARIE KRUGLANSKI: The need for
cognitive closure
is the need for certainty and
the need to

36:26.184 --> 36:30.455 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be confident about a topic, the
need to know
for sure.

36:30.488 --> 36:36.227 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Kruglanski and
his team have
authored reams of research on
the Sri Lankan

36:36.261 --> 36:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
terror group known as the
Liberation Tigers
of Tamil Eelam, the Tamil
Tigers.

36:41.966 --> 36:47.639 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He discovered a clear link
between feelings
of self-worth and the desire to
join a group.

36:47.672 --> 36:52.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARIE KRUGLANSKI: You feel that
you're humiliated,
that you're insignificant, you
do not matter.

36:52.877 --> 36:57.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that predisposes people to
listen to ideologies
that tell you, I will tell you
how you're

36:57.415 --> 36:59.184 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
going to matter.

36:59.217 --> 37:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You're going to matter -- and
this is in the
case of ISIS and radicalization
-- you're

37:02.120 --> 37:04.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to matter by joining the
fight.

37:04.456 --> 37:09.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Kruglanski has
tested this
theory with a simple experiment,
which he

37:09.861 --> 37:11.463 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
replicated for us.

37:11.496 --> 37:15.934 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our subjects, four University of
Maryland
undergraduates.

37:15.967 --> 37:19.571 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Graduate student Marina
Chernikova presided
over the experiment.

37:19.604 --> 37:21.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARINA CHERNIKOVA, University of
Maryland
Graduate Student: The purpose of
this experiment

37:21.372 --> 37:24.209 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is to provide -- is to explore
the evolutionary
hunting hypothesis.

37:24.242 --> 37:28.813 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They all played a
simple video
game called the Duck Hunt.

37:28.847 --> 37:34.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The game was set to be
impossibly hard for
two of them, and incredibly easy
for the other

37:34.652 --> 37:36.488 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
two.

37:36.521 --> 37:41.659 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were told a score of 100 or
more predicts
all kinds of success in life.

37:41.693 --> 37:44.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARINA CHERNIKOVA: But scores
lower than 100
strongly predict failure.

37:44.696 --> 37:46.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So you're going to be playing
that game today.

37:46.598 --> 37:48.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Ben Weinberg (ph)
had it easy.

37:48.867 --> 37:54.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was knocking ducks out of the
sky right
and left, and waltzed to the
100-point threshold.

37:54.172 --> 38:00.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when it was Mara Lins' turn
in the hot
seat, there were no sitting
ducks, not even

38:00.445 --> 38:02.147 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
close.

38:02.180 --> 38:04.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARA LINS, University of
Maryland Student:
I felt really frustrated,
because the duck

38:04.182 --> 38:08.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was just going so fast, I
couldn't ever really
click on it that well, and the
scores just

38:08.786 --> 38:10.321 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
kept going more and more down.

38:10.355 --> 38:12.223 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, it made me really
uncomfortable, actually.

38:12.257 --> 38:17.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: They took a
survey that included
two dozen questions designed to
assess people's

38:17.262 --> 38:19.297 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
need for support from a group.

38:19.330 --> 38:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ARIE KRUGLANSKI: So, this person
seems to
be scoring very high on
interdependence.

38:22.834 --> 38:25.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you know what condition was
he in?

38:25.537 --> 38:27.872 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARINA CHERNIKOVA: Yes, this one
was in the
failure condition.

38:27.906 --> 38:29.240 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ARIE KRUGLANSKI: In the failure
condition.

38:29.274 --> 38:30.241 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
OK.

38:30.275 --> 38:31.676 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That's very interesting.

38:31.709 --> 38:34.279 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're successful, you feel
relatively
independent of your group.

38:34.312 --> 38:35.747 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can have it on your own.

38:35.780 --> 38:36.814 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You do not need the group.

38:36.848 --> 38:38.850 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
